				\begin{document}$${{\rm{\rho }}}_{T}(\lambda )=\frac{8\pi hc}{{\lambda }^{5}}\frac{1}{{e}^{hc/\lambda {k}_{B}T}-1}$$\end{document}where h is Planck’s constant with a value of 6.626 × 10−34 J·s, c is the speed of light with a value of 2.998 × 108 m·s−1, λ is the wavelength in m, kB is Boltzmann’s constant with a value of 1.381 × 10−23 J·K−1, and T is the absolute temperature of the object in K.

The irradiance E, the flux received by a surface per unit area, is given by E = c ·ρ. Black body assumption includes the isotropic diffusion of thermal radiation. With this assumption, the plane irradiance Ed is given by Ed = E/4, where E is total irradiance. Collectively, the spectral plane irradiance is given byEdT(λ)=2πhc2λ51ehc/λkBT−1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
